nt|^b@2^z@3|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Precision makes no distinction between hands that do or don't contain a weak doubleton.

Semi-balanced hands with a 5-card major are NOT opened with 1NT, however, even if they are relatively weak.

An honourless suit, however, such as @H97642 might be opened with 1NT if the rest of the hand was semi-balanced ie: treat it as a 4-card suit.

Ok, that's about the only Precision-specific part of the lesson.  As I said at the start, you can fit literally ANY scheme of responses that you like over a Precision 1NT Opening or any other system's natural 1NT Opening, for that matter, since it does not affect the REST of the system in the slightest.

If, therefore, you wish to play McGruders 2nd variation in E Minor or Reverse Double-Barrelled 2-way Marionette Stayman, then please be my guest (and may God have mercy on you <grin>).

What range NT you play DOES affect other things (the 1@C and 1@D Openings mainly) so do think about the implications before you stray from a 13-15 strength.

Before we get going, is there ANYONE here who has NEVER played any kind of transfers before? I'm hoping most of you have, but assume that some of you might not have played full 4-suit transfers yet.

The original definition of Precision specifies the use of 2-way Stayman, ie: 

^d@21NT - 2@C  is non-forcing ordinary Stayman
1NT - 2@D  is FORCING Stayman
1NT - 2@H  is a natural weak takeout, and
1NT - 2@S  is also a natural weak takeout.

^b@2I have never liked this scheme (and very few Precision pairs use it) and I do not propose to teach it to you.

Firstly it is inefficient and does not give the flexibility that transfers afford.  Secondly it is complex but to no great effect, in my view.
