cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Instead, I will outline the scheme for Normal but non-promissory Stayman and 4-way Transfers, and suggest next week one innovation that I and an old partner of mine came up with about 38 years ago, which you may wish to try, a 2-way 2@D response.

1NT - 2@C   is Stayman.

I'm not going to go into the basic mechanics of Stayman as it is normally the very first convention that any newcomer to Bridge is taught.

Later on today I will spend a little time on the differences in meaning between sequences that use Stayman and those that use transfers ie: where you end up showing 5+ cards in one major and 4-cards in the other.

I mentioned "non-promissory" Stayman earlier.

This is the norm when using 4-way transfers where 1NT - 2NT is a transfer to Diamonds.

"Non-promissory" simply means that 1NT-2@C does NOT guarantee that Responder holds a 4-card Major at all, since raises to 2NT have to go VIA Stayman  (because 1NT - 2NT is a transfer to Diamonds).


One aspect of Stayman is often forgotten, to the bidder's detriment.

There is only ONE requirement for the use of Stayman and it is this: If you decide to use Stayman, you MUST be in a position to cope sensibly with ANY of the 3 possible responses.

In general, if any one of those responses would "fix" you, then you should not use Stayman at all.
|
