nt|^b@2^z@3|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  There is, therefore, no minimum point count necessary to use Stayman eg: a hand like 
  @Sxxxx   @Hxxxxxx   @Dx   @Cxx     is very suitable for use with Stayman, because over 2@D responder bids 2@H, and they pass if Opener bids either Major in response to the Stayman enquiry.

What you MUST consider before using Stayman is this: If ANY of the 3 possible responses to Stayman would embarrass you and leave you without a sensible course of action, then you can bet your bottom dollar that that is what Opener will respond, and you should NOT use Stayman at all.

Suppose partner opens a 13-15 1NT and you hold    @SQJ7x  @HKJTx  @Dx  @CJTxx 

This is NOT a hand on which to use Stayman: A 2@H or 2@S rebid by Opener will be fine, but a 2@D response will leave you with nowhere safe to go since you do not have enough strength to bid 2NT over 2@D.


