nt|^b@2^z@3|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Just in case some of you have never yet used Transfers (and, amazingly, such people are more numerous than you might imagine) I will just outline the way transfers work and the reason they are so effective and popular: Transfers work by injecting an extra round of bidding.

Instead of bidding YOUR suit, you bid the suit below that and this in turn asks your PARTNER to bid your suit for you.

You are then free to pass or bid on depending on your strength.

They also facilitate Opener's hand being Declarer, which is often an advantage.

Thus 1NT-2@H requests that partner bids 2@S.

If you have a weak takeout, you simply pass over 2@S.

If you have a semi-balanced hand with 5-card spades that is at least worth an invitation, then you can bid NT's at the appropriate level to show this.

Alternatively you can invite or bid game in spades, or show a second suit if you hold one.

This is more flexible than a scheme where 1NT - 2@S is a weak-takeout and 1NT - 3@S is game-forcing.

Moreover, it increases the chance that the 1NT bidder who will normally have the stronger hand will end up as declarer with their strength hidden.

Transfers normally guarantee that you hold at least a 5-card suit in the suit you're transferring into.|
