cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Partner can "break" the transfer with an exceptionally suitable hand ie: maximum with good support for your suit.

Thus the sequence 1NT - 2@H(Xfer to @S) - 3@C would probably show a maximum 1NT, good 4-card support for
@SSpades@S and first-round control of Clubs, ie: the Ace. 

Another method for breaking transfers is to show a "worthless" doubleton if you have one, instead of cue-bidding your cheapest outside Ace.

Both methods work ok.


In this system we tend to cue-bid our cheapest Ace over 1NT - 2@H, but for various reasons we show worthless doubletons over 1NT - 2@D if the Diamond is 2-way (More on that next week).


Transfers should NEVER EVER be "broken" out of weakness or a lack of support for partner's suit.

If, for example, you've had a brainstorm and opened 1NT with  @SAx  @Hxx  @DKxx  @CKQJxxx  and the bidding goes
1NT - 2@D - ??   you must not bid 3@C just because you don't like Hearts.

For all you know partner might be sat there with @hAKQxxxx.
|
