cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  In a 1NT sequence, RESPONDER is ABSOLUTELY and ALWAYS the Captain of the hand.

The 1NT Opener should stick to all these criteria, however, because partner may have a very weak hand and not be remotely interested in game.

Breaking the transfer inevitably means that you must play this contract at least at the 3-level.

But breaking the transfer like this can get you to some excellent very thin games, especially when Responder has a reasonable 6 or 7-card Minor and you have a fit.


As I said before, there are 2 common methods when breaking transfers to a MAJOR: 

You can either cue-bid your CHEAPEST 1st-round Control ie: Ace, 

OR you can show a "useless doubleton" ie: xx which will give partner some indication where your HCP are by a process of elimination and give them an idea of how well the hands are fitting.


Both of these methods are fine and both are BETTER than simply raising to 3 of partner's Major rather than 2, which tells them absolutely NOTHING extra about your hand.
