cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Ok, back to Stayman.

The more astute of you will by now have realised that if  1NT - 2NT  is a transfer to DIAMONDS then -

How do you invite partner to 3NT   with a balanced 13-14 opposite a 10-12 1NT, 

OR  with a balanced 10-11 points opposite a 13-15 1NT Opening? 

The answer is that you HAVE to go via Stayman (or the 2-way 2@D as we'll see next week).


Since we use an almost identical system of responses when Opener ends up rebidding 2NT to show a strong balanced hand, the same applies there  - raise to 3NT have to go via Puppet Stayman since  ...2NT - 3NT is a transfer to Diamonds.

The effect of this is that the use of Stayman does NOT promise possession of a 4-card Major hence the term "Non-promissory Stayman" and this does have an effect on the Stayman sequences.

If you are not using 4-suit transfers then a sequence like  1NT - 2@C - 2@H - 2NT  suggests that Responder has a 4-card SPADE suit and Opener will inevitably bid 3@S or 4@S if they also have one.

This is not the case in this system of responses.

If responder has 4-card Spades and NOT 4-card Hearts, then over  1NT - 2@C - 2@H  they rebid 2@S to show the Spades and a hand worth at least an invitation.
