cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So when should you use Stayman and when Transfers, if you appear to have a choice?  Well there are a number of choices, but the main thing to aim for is a system of responses that is entirely consistent and intuitive.

The main area of choice is when you have one 4-card Major and one 5-card or longer Major:

If you transfer to one suit and then show a second suit, this is ALWAYS game-forcing (or perhaps just invitational if you are a passed hand). 

So a sequence like  1NT - 2@H - 2@S - 3@H  is 100 percent game-forcing with 5-card or longer Spades and 4-card or longer Hearts.

That in a nutshell demonstrates the difference between Staymanic sequences and ones using transfers, especially where both majors are shown.    Therefore -

1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 2@S  is a weak takeout with 4-card hearts and 5+-card spades.

1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 3@H  shows an INVITATIONAL hand with 4-card spades and 5-card or longer hearts.

1NT - 2@H - 2@S - 3@H  shows a game-forcing hand with 4-card or longer hearts and 5-card or longer spades.

You can choose to use the SMOLEN convention here if you like whereby 

1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 3@H  shows 4-card Hearts and 5-cards or longer SPADES, invitational strength, and

1NT - 2@C - 2@D - 3@S  shows 4-card Spades and 5-card or longer HEARTS.

Personally, I'm not a great fan of Smolen, but it's for you to choose.

It doesn't impact on the rest of the system.
