cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  As we'll see next week, we actually have TWO ways of making a balanced invitation to game, one involving Stayman, as we've seen this week, and one involving the 2-way 2@D response, as we'll see next week 

kritter2:  It is not as valuable (when playing weak no trumps) to play Smolen ?

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Indeed, which is one of the reasons I seen no huge advantage for Precision users.

In our case, the Staymanic method is a MILD invitation and the invitation using the 2-way 2@D is a STRONGER invitation More of that next week Last lap: Given the availability of transfers, the need to keep 3-level jump-shifts for game-forcing hands is greatly reduced.

Super-Precision uses these bids to initiate Asking Bid sequences, but in the absence of these, you might like to consider using these for UNBALANCED single-suited hands with at least a 6-card suit, definitely not interested in playing in No Trumps, that are nonetheless worth a mild invitation.

If you adopt these methods and ONLY if, then the implications of a sequence such as  
1NT - 2@D - 2@H - 3@H  is that either the hearts are only 5-card in length or responder IS happy to consider playing in No Trumps opposite a good hand.  Ultimately you have to work out the meanings of these different sequences with your partner.

Lastly In this system, we also use Texas Transfers  1NT - 4@D  and  1NT - 4@H  to show game-going hands with a 6+-card Major.

The upshot of this is that a sequence such as  1NT - 2@H - 2@S - 4@S  is a mild slam try, since a hand only interested in game would bid   1NT - 4@h - 4@S.

Similarly a sequence such as  1NT - 2@S - 3@C - 3NT  is a mild slam try, since a hand only interested in game would just bid   1NT - 3NT.

